{# Expansion prompt: produce N rephrasings of one memory hard-case prototype side.

   Variables:
     - count: number of rephrasings to generate
     - prototype_user_message
     - prototype_assistant_response
     - prototype_memories_json: JSON array of memories_to_extract (preserved verbatim)
     - prototype_negatives_json: JSON array of negative_extractions
     - prototype_rationale
     - explicit_command: "remember" | "forget" | null
     - pair_type: e.g. "implicit_vs_explicit_preference"
     - today_iso, today_plus_7_iso, today_plus_30_iso: date anchors
#}
You generate {{ count }} REPHRASINGS of a single user/assistant memory turn
for an adversarial training set. Every rephrasing must preserve the SAME
EXTRACTION DECISION — same memories_to_extract, same negative_extractions,
same explicit_command. The goal is variety in surface form (register,
sentence shape, word choice) without changing what should or shouldn't be
extracted.

ANCHOR: today is {{ today_iso }}. Treat any "this week" / "next week" cues
relative to that date. Where the prototype carries a temporary_context
expiration_iso_date, your rephrasings must use the SAME date.

OUTPUT FORMAT (strict): a JSON array of EXACTLY {{ count }} objects. No prose,
no Markdown code fence, no thinking. The first character of your reply must
be `[` and the last must be `]`.

Each object must have exactly two fields:

  "user_message":        rephrased user turn (string)
  "assistant_response":  natural assistant reply (string, can vary too)

The memories_to_extract / negative_extractions / explicit_command fields are
FIXED by the prototype — the driver applies them to all your rephrasings.
You only produce the user/assistant text.

PROTOTYPE:
  pair_type:           {{ pair_type }}
  user_message:        {{ prototype_user_message | tojson }}
  assistant_response:  {{ prototype_assistant_response | tojson }}
  memories_to_extract: {{ prototype_memories_json }}
  negative_extractions: {{ prototype_negatives_json }}
  explicit_command:    {{ explicit_command | default('null') | tojson }}
  rationale:           {{ prototype_rationale }}

VARIATION RULES:

  1. Vary the SURFACE FORM substantially — different word order, different
     sentence shape, more casual / more formal, sometimes a fragment.
  2. Keep all SIGNAL WORDS that drive the extraction decision. If the
     prototype's extraction hinges on "always" or "every Sunday", at least
     2 of your variants must keep that signal (or an equivalent like
     "every time" / "weekly"). If the prototype hinges on "today" or
     "this morning" to mark a one-off, your variants must keep that
     temporal one-off marker.
  3. The assistant response can vary in tone but must remain plausible.
     Sometimes acknowledging, sometimes redirecting, sometimes neutral —
     never robotic.
  4. Do NOT produce duplicates. Each rephrasing must be substantively
     different from every other rephrasing AND from the prototype itself.
  5. NEVER flip the extraction decision. If the prototype is in
     negative_extractions territory (one-off, transient), your variants
     must remain transient. If the prototype is durable, your variants
     must remain durable.

EXEMPLAR (different topic — for shape only, do NOT copy):

  Prototype: user_message="I always order an Americano when I get coffee."
  Output:
  [
    {"user_message":"americanos every time, no exceptions","assistant_response":"Strong and clean — I get it."},
    {"user_message":"my go-to coffee order is always an americano","assistant_response":"What roast do you like?"},
    {"user_message":"I never get anything but americanos at coffee shops","assistant_response":"Reliable choice."},
    {"user_message":"americano is always my coffee shop order","assistant_response":"Solid pick."},
    {"user_message":"every time I'm in a coffee shop I order an americano","assistant_response":"Consistent."}
  ]

Now output the JSON array of {{ count }} rephrasings of the prototype above.
Output ONLY the array.
